@startuml Collection Update Sequence Diagram

!define BLUE_COLOR #4A90E2
!define GREEN_COLOR #7ED321
!define ORANGE_COLOR #F5A623
!define PURPLE_COLOR #9013FE

actor "User" as User BLUE_COLOR
participant "Frontend\nApplication" as Frontend ORANGE_COLOR
participant "API Engine\n(/api/[model])" as APIEngine PURPLE_COLOR
participant "Collection\nConfig" as Config GREEN_COLOR
participant "Database\n(PostgreSQL)" as Database GREEN_COLOR

== Collection Update Operation ==
box "Update Collection" #LightGreen
    User -> Frontend: Edit collection properties\n(name, code, data)
    Frontend -> APIEngine: PUT /api/collection/update/{code}\n{ updatedCollectionFields }
    activate APIEngine

    APIEngine -> Config: Load Collection configuration
    Config -> Config: Validate update access permissions
    Config -> Config: Validate allowed update fields\n- name: Collection display name\n- code: Unique collection identifier\n- data: Collection configuration data
    Config -> Database: Update collection record by code
    activate Database
    Database --> Config: Collection updated successfully
    deactivate Database

    APIEngine --> Frontend: Return updated collection data
    deactivate APIEngine
    Frontend -> Frontend: Refresh collection display
    Frontend --> User: Show updated collection
end box

== Error Handling ==
alt Update Fails
    APIEngine -> Frontend: Return error response\n(400, 403, 404, 500)
    Frontend -> Frontend: Handle error state
    Frontend --> User: Display error message
end alt

== Notes ==
note over Frontend, Database
    **Collection Update Features:**
    - Simple field-based updates
    - Code-based identification for updates
    - Direct database modifications

    **Allowed Update Fields:**
    - name: Human-readable collection name
    - code: Unique identifier (used for updates)
    - data: Collection configuration and settings

    **Update Characteristics:**
    - No complex lifecycle hooks
    - No draft state management
    - Direct field validation
    - Simple permission checking

    **Use Cases:**
    - Updating collection metadata
    - Modifying collection configuration
    - Renaming collections
    - Updating collection data structures
end note

@enduml
